n Overview Frogeye Leaf Spot FLS is the most impor
most important foliar disease of soybean especiall
especially in the southern US The disease has bee
se has been occurring more frequently in northern
northern soybeangrowing areas and has increasingl
ncreasingly suppressed soybean yields in the north
the northern US in recent years FLS is caused by
caused by the fungus Cercospora sojina Young soybe
oung soybean leaves are most susceptible while old
while older leaves tend to be more resistant Leaf
stant Leaf symptoms are first noticeable after pla
after plants begin to bloom Infection occurs duri
ccurs during warm humid weather with cloudy days a
udy days and frequent rain When these conditions p
nditions persist infection can spread from leaves
om leaves to pods seeds and stems The pathogen sur
thogen survives between growing seasons on soybean
on soybean residue in the field and can survive on
survive on seeds in storage When planted infected
infected seed may give rise to infected seedlings
seedlings Scouting Scout for FLS when soybean pla
oybean plants begin to bloom Scout in at least one
least one area for each 10 acres of the field Dis
field Disease incidence and severity can be highl
n be highly variable from field to field and even
and even within a field due to environmental cond
ental conditions For example disease will likely b
l likely be more severe on the west side of a nort
of a northsouth oriented fence row with tall tree
tall trees or wooded area because the trees provi
rees provide early morning shade that can increase
n increase the amount of drying time for leaves we
leaves wetted by dew rain or overhead irrigation
rrigation Symptoms FLS appears as circular tan to
ar tan to gray spots on the leaves surrounded by v
unded by very pronounced dark purple margins They
gins They are most often the size of the end of a
end of a pencil eraser about  inch in diameter S
diameter Smaller lesions can coalesce into larger
to larger lesions When disease pressure is high on
is high on susceptible varieties spots can also be
an also be found on the stems pods and seeds Lesio
eeds Lesions on pods are circular to elongate and
ngate and slightly sunken with a reddishbrown colo
brown color As pod lesions age they become brown t
me brown to light gray with narrow darkbrown borde
rown borders The pathogen can penetrate through th
through the pod wall and infect the developing see
loping seeds Symptoms on seeds appear as conspicuo
conspicuous light to dark gray or brown areas tha
areas that can range from specks to large blotche
ge blotches covering the entire seed coat and the
t and the seed coat may crack or flake Management
anagement Assessing the risks Frogeye Leaf Spot de
af Spot develops and spreads during warm cloudy hu
cloudy humid weather when rain is frequent Spores
ent Spores called conidia are carried by wind or r
wind or rain and the disease can spread rapidly u
rapidly under these conditions This disease will
ease will be rare when the weather is dry and hot
y and hot Young expanding leaves are highly suscep
hly susceptible while fully expanded leaves are mo
ves are more resistant to infection Even with arti
with artificial inoculation under ideal condition
conditions lesions seldom develop on fully expand
lly expanded leaves The frogeye leaf spot pathogen
t pathogen survives in infected seeds or in soybea
in soybean residue The fungus can survive in soyb
ve in soybean residue until the residue completely
completely decomposes Seed infection is common The
common The germination rate of infected seed may b
seed may be reduced and the resulting seedlings ar
edlings are usually weak Spores produced on the co
on the cotyledons of infected seedlings are the m
are the main source of inoculum for the leaf phas
leaf phase of the disease The disease is best man
s best managed using varieties with the Rcs 3 sour
Rcs 3 source of resistance which has maintained it
ntained its effectiveness against currently known
tly known US populations of C sojina In fields whe
fields where very high levels of disease develop b
develop burying residue andor using crop rotation
p rotation become very important C sojina is known
a is known to overwinter in some North Central sta
entral states and planting soybeans back into infe
into infested residue increases the chance of an
nce of an epidemic occurring the following season
ng season if environmental conditions are favorabl
e favorable Where tillage is used residue should b
e should be fully buried If residue cannot be buri
ot be buried then rotating out of soybean for at l
n for at least two years will help reduce risk It
e risk It is not yet known how many years the path
s the pathogen can survive on residue but soybeans
t soybeans should not be planted for at least one
least one year and then a resistant variety should
ety should be used When FLS lesions are found on p
found on plants prior to growth stage R3 fungicide
fungicide applications may be useful on susceptib
susceptible varieties however specific thresholds
thresholds have not been set Fungicide efficacy is
fficacy is entirely dependent on the occurrence of
urrence of weather conditions that continue to fav
nue to favor infection and lesion development Fung
pment Fungicides Research has shown that the FLS p

esistance to Group 11 strobilurin fungicides QoI a
ides QoI after just a single application Group 3 t

gal leaf disease of soybean that occurs wherever s

hen weather conditions are rainy and humid The dow
id The downy mildew pathogen Peronospora manshuric
manshurica survives in crop residue and on the se
on the seed surface The pathogen is in the same g
the same group of water mold pathogens that cause
hat cause Phytophthora root rot and Pythium seedli

blight of potato Like these other pathogens the pa
ens the pathogen that causes soybean downy mildew
ny mildew has swimming spores and needs water or h

res are carried onto plants by wind and rain and i
rain and infection can spread quickly through a fi
rough a field during periods of cool wet or humid
or humid weather Scouting Downy mildew is very we
is very weatherdependent and is most likely to occ
ely to occur during periods of cool wet weather Yo
weather Younger leaves are more susceptible to dow
ble to downy mildew than older leaves so the disea
the disease will generally appear first on the up
on the upper surface of young leaves Look for pal
ok for pale green to light yellow spots which enla
which enlarge into pale to bright yellow spots The
spots The center of the spots eventually turns br

o palepurplish spores on the lower leaf surface du
surface during humid weather The presence of this
e of this sporulation is diagnostic for downy mild
downy mildew If in doubt place the leaf in a plast
in a plastic bag with a moist paper towel and exam
l and examine again for sporulation in about 6 hou
bout 6 hours Some soybean varieties express mild l
ess mild leaf distortion that may resemble symptom
le symptoms caused by common soybean viruses Pods

bvious external symptoms Infected seed has a dull
as a dull white appearance and is partially or com
lly or completely covered with a pale coating of f
ating of fungal spores which can be confused with
used with white mold Management The disease rarely
ase rarely reduces yield so fungicides are not rec
re not recommended for downy mildew management Imp
gement Implementing cultural controls to reduce th
reduce the risk of downy mildew is generally all
rally all that is needed Plant clean seed Growers
d Growers planting nonGMO varieties should use cer
ld use certified diseasefree seed Do not plant see
plant seed from fields infected the previous year
vious year Rotate crops and manage crop residue Th
residue The downy mildew fungus survives in crop r
in crop residue and on the surface of seed Longer
eed Longer crop rotations and placing crop residue
op residues into contact with the soil after harve
fter harvest will help reduce future infections Re
